Note:
HCL (HashiCorp Configuration Language / Terraform) Translation Round-Trip Probe

End-to-end proof that the HCL translation pipeline is REAL, not a skeleton:

    HCL source
      -> hcl_lexer    (tokenize: keywords, strings, numbers, operators,
                       interpolation markers, comments)
      -> hcl_parser   (build HCL block/attribute/expression AST)
      -> hcl_to_hir   (lower each block to a HIR class/variable carrying
                       hcl_* metadata; attributes become HIR fields)
      -> hir_to_hcl   (emit the HIR declaration stream back to HCL text)

The probe feeds a representative Terraform document containing: a provider
block; an input variable block with a typed default; a managed resource block
holding string, number, boolean, and list attribute values, a cross-block
reference (var.region) and a nested block; an output block referencing the
resource; a data source block; and a locals block with two bindings.

It then:
  1. Drives source -> tokens -> AST -> HIR (HIR1) and asserts the HIR module
     has the expected declaration count and that the first emission already
     carries the right block types/labels/attributes.
  2. Emits HIR1 back to HCL text and asserts the text is non-empty.
  3. RE-PARSES the emitted text into a SECOND HIR (HIR2) and asserts ON THE
     SECOND EMISSION that every structural fact survived: block kinds, labels,
     attribute keys, attribute value payloads (string/number/bool/list shape),
     and nested-block survival. A recursive comparator proves HIR1 and HIR2 are
     structurally equal. Structural (not byte) equality is the correct
     semantic-equivalence check because the backend canonicalises whitespace.

Exit code: number of failed assertions (0 == all passed). No exit_with_code.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/hcl/hcl_lexer.runa" as HCLLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/hcl/hcl_parser.runa" as HCLParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/hcl/hcl_to_hir.runa" as HCLFrontend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/hcl/hir_to_hcl.runa" as HCLBackend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pipeline driver: HCL source -> HIR module
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The HCL pipeline has no single source-to-HIR convenience, so the probe owns the
three-stage chain explicitly: create_hcl_lexer/tokenize produces the token list,
create_hcl_parser/parse_hcl_configuration produces the block AST, and
translate_hcl_to_hir lowers that AST to a HIR module of class/variable
declarations. Returning the module pointer (or 0 on any stage failure) lets the
caller assert on a single value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "hcl_source_to_hir" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_hcl_lexer from HCLLexer with source
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let tokens be proc tokenize from HCLLexer with lexer
    If tokens is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let parser be proc create_hcl_parser from HCLParser with tokens
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast be proc parse_hcl_configuration from HCLParser with parser
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir_module be proc translate_hcl_to_hir from HCLFrontend with ast
    Return hir_module
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR declaration accessors (mirror the backend's read contract)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The probe walks the same declaration list the backend walks: every block becomes
a HIR_CLASS (or a const HIR_VARIABLE for locals) appended to the module. These
accessors centralise the list reads so the comparator and the content assertions
share one contract.
@End Reasoning
Process called "module_decl_count" takes hir_module as Integer returns Integer:
    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with hir_module
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc list_length from List with declarations
End Process

Process called "module_decl_at" takes hir_module as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with hir_module
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc list_get from List with declarations, index
End Process

@Reasoning:
Finds the first declaration whose hcl_block_type metadata equals the requested
kind and whose primary label equals the requested name. Resources/data/module/
provider expose their name through dedicated metadata keys; variable/output
expose it through the class name. The probe asks by (kind, name) so the
assertion is order-independent: registry iteration order is not guaranteed.
@End Reasoning
Process called "find_block" takes hir_module as Integer, kind as Integer, name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count be proc module_decl_count with hir_module
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc module_decl_at with hir_module, i
        Let decl_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with decl
        If decl_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CLASS:
            Let block_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with decl, "hcl_block_type"
            Let kind_matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with block_type, kind
            If kind_matches is equal to 1:
                Let decl_name be proc block_primary_name with decl
                Let name_matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with decl_name, name
                If name_matches is equal to 1:
                    Return decl
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the block's primary identifying name. Resource/data blocks identify by
their type label (hcl_resource_type / hcl_data_type); module/provider by their
single name label; variable/output by the class name. Falls back to class name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "block_primary_name" takes decl as Integer returns Integer:
    Let block_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with decl, "hcl_block_type"

    Let is_resource be proc string_equals from StringCore with block_type, "resource"
    If is_resource is equal to 1:
        Return proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with decl, "hcl_resource_type"
    End If

    Let is_data be proc string_equals from StringCore with block_type, "data"
    If is_data is equal to 1:
        Return proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with decl, "hcl_data_type"
    End If

    Let is_module be proc string_equals from StringCore with block_type, "module"
    If is_module is equal to 1:
        Return proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with decl, "hcl_module_name"
    End If

    Let is_provider be proc string_equals from StringCore with block_type, "provider"
    If is_provider is equal to 1:
        Return proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with decl, "hcl_provider_name"
    End If

    Return proc hir_get_class_name from HIR with decl
End Process

@Reasoning:
Looks up a body attribute by name on a block (HIR class). Body attributes are
HIR_FIELD class members carrying a name and an initializer expression; this
returns the initializer node, or 0 when the attribute is absent.
@End Reasoning
Process called "block_attr_value" takes decl as Integer, attr_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let members be proc hir_get_class_members from HIR with decl
    If members is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let member_count be proc list_length from List with members
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than member_count:
        Let member be proc list_get from List with members, i
        Let member_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with member
        If member_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FIELD:
            Let field_name be proc hir_get_field_name from HIR with member
            Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with field_name, attr_name
            If matches is equal to 1:
                Return proc hir_get_field_initializer from HIR with member
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Counts nested-block members (HIR classes appearing as members of an outer block).
Used to assert that a resource's nested block survived the round trip.
@End Reasoning
Process called "block_nested_count" takes decl as Integer returns Integer:
    Let members be proc hir_get_class_members from HIR with decl
    If members is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let member_count be proc list_length from List with members
    Let nested be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than member_count:
        Let member be proc list_get from List with members, i
        Let member_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with member
        If member_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CLASS:
            Set nested to nested plus 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return nested
End Process

@Reasoning:
Renders an HIR value expression to a comparable text key for structural value
equality. String literals become their content (numbers, tagged hcl_number, are
also string literals so they compare by exact source text); booleans become
"true"/"false"; identifiers and member references become their dotted text; lists
become "list:N" where N is the element count. This captures attribute-value shape
and payload survival without depending on the backend's emitter internals.
@End Reasoning
Process called "value_key" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return "<none>"
    End If

    Let node_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with node

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_STRING_LITERAL:
        Return proc hir_get_string_literal_value from HIR with node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BOOL_LITERAL:
        Let bv be proc hir_get_bool_literal_value from HIR with node
        If bv is equal to 1:
            Return "true"
        Otherwise:
            Return "false"
        End If
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER:
        Return proc hir_get_identifier_name from HIR with node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_MEMBER_EXPR:
        Let object be proc hir_get_member_object from HIR with node
        Let member_name be proc hir_get_member_name from HIR with node
        Let object_key be proc value_key with object
        Let dotted be proc string_concat from StringPrim with object_key, "."
        Set dotted to proc string_concat from StringPrim with dotted, member_name
        Return dotted
    End If

    If node_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LIST_LITERAL:
        Let elements be proc hir_get_list_elements from HIR with node
        Let elem_count be 0
        If elements is not equal to 0:
            Set elem_count to proc list_length from List with elements
        End If
        Let prefix be "list:"
        Let count_str be proc value_key_int_to_string with elem_count
        Return proc string_concat from StringPrim with prefix, count_str
    End If

    Return "<expr>"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tiny non-negative integer-to-decimal-string helper used only by value_key for
the list-length tag. Implemented locally because the probe must not depend on
runtime string-format helpers that vary across primitive layers.
@End Reasoning
Process called "value_key_int_to_string" takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return "0"
    End If

    Let digits be ""
    Let value be n
    While value is greater than 0:
        Let digit be value modulo by 10
        Let digit_char be 48 plus digit
        Let digit_str be proc char_to_string from StringCore with digit_char
        Set digits to proc string_concat from StringPrim with digit_str, digits
        Set value to value divided by 10
    End While
    Return digits
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Recursive structural comparator: HIR1 vs HIR2
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Two HIR modules are structurally equal when they have the same declaration count
and, for every block in the first module, a matching block in the second exists
with the same kind, label, attribute keys, attribute value keys, and nested-block
count. The walk is driven from module 1 and each block is located in module 2 by
(kind, name), so it is order-independent. Returns 1 on full structural equality,
0 otherwise.
@End Reasoning
Process called "modules_structurally_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let count_a be proc module_decl_count with a
    Let count_b be proc module_decl_count with b
    If count_a is not equal to count_b:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let decl_a be proc module_decl_at with a, i
        Let decl_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with decl_a

        If decl_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CLASS:
            Let kind be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with decl_a, "hcl_block_type"
            Let name be proc block_primary_name with decl_a
            Let decl_b be proc find_block with b, kind, name
            If decl_b is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            Let blocks_equal be proc blocks_structurally_equal with decl_a, decl_b
            If blocks_equal is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two blocks are structurally equal when every attribute (HIR_FIELD member) of the
first has a same-named attribute in the second whose value_key matches, and the
nested-block counts match. Attribute keys and value payloads are the load-bearing
content; comparing them by name+value_key proves both key and value survived the
re-parse.
@End Reasoning
Process called "blocks_structurally_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let nested_a be proc block_nested_count with a
    Let nested_b be proc block_nested_count with b
    If nested_a is not equal to nested_b:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let members be proc hir_get_class_members from HIR with a
    If members is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let member_count be proc list_length from List with members
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than member_count:
        Let member be proc list_get from List with members, i
        Let member_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with member
        If member_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FIELD:
            Let field_name be proc hir_get_field_name from HIR with member
            Let value_a be proc hir_get_field_initializer from HIR with member
            Let value_b be proc block_attr_value with b, field_name
            If value_b is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If

            Let key_a be proc value_key with value_a
            Let key_b be proc value_key with value_b
            Let keys_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with key_a, key_b
            If keys_match is equal to 0:
                Return 0
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main probe
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Runs the full pipeline twice (source -> HIR1, emitted-text -> HIR2) and asserts
both the first-emission content and the second-emission structural survival. The
return value is the failed-assertion count so a CI gate can treat 0 as success.
@End Reasoning
Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "HCL translation round-trip"

    Note: Representative Terraform configuration. Newlines are explicit \n.
    Let source be "provider \"aws\" {\n  region = var.region\n}\n\nvariable \"region\" {\n  default = \"us-east-1\"\n}\n\nresource \"aws_instance\" \"web\" {\n  ami = \"ami-12345\"\n  instance_count = 3\n  monitoring = true\n  tags = [\"web\", \"prod\"]\n  region = var.region\n  network {\n    subnet = \"subnet-abc\"\n  }\n}\n\noutput \"web_id\" {\n  value = aws_instance.web.id\n}\n\ndata \"aws_ami\" \"ubuntu\" {\n  owner = \"099720109477\"\n}\n\nlocals {\n  env = \"production\"\n  team = \"platform\"\n}"

    Note: --- Stage 1: source -> HIR1 ---
    Let hir1 be proc hcl_source_to_hir with source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "pipeline produced HIR module", hir1

    Let root_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with hir1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "HIR root is module", root_type, HIR.HIR_MODULE

    Note: provider, variable, resource, output, data, plus two locals = 7 declarations
    Let decl_count be proc module_decl_count with hir1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "HIR module has 7 declarations", decl_count, 7

    Note: --- Stage 1 content: provider block ---
    Let provider_block be proc find_block with hir1, "provider", "aws"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "provider \"aws\" present", provider_block
    Let provider_region be proc block_attr_value with provider_block, "region"
    Let provider_region_key be proc value_key with provider_region
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "provider region references var.region", provider_region_key, "var.region"

    Note: --- variable block with default ---
    Let variable_block be proc find_block with hir1, "variable", "region"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "variable \"region\" present", variable_block
    Let var_default be proc block_attr_value with variable_block, "default"
    Let var_default_key be proc value_key with var_default
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "variable default is 'us-east-1'", var_default_key, "us-east-1"

    Note: --- resource block: string, number, bool, list, reference, nested block ---
    Let resource_block be proc find_block with hir1, "resource", "aws_instance"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "resource aws_instance present", resource_block
    Let res_name be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with resource_block, "hcl_resource_name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "resource name is 'web'", res_name, "web"

    Let ami_value be proc block_attr_value with resource_block, "ami"
    Let ami_key be proc value_key with ami_value
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "resource ami string value", ami_key, "ami-12345"
    Let count_value be proc block_attr_value with resource_block, "instance_count"
    Let count_key be proc value_key with count_value
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "resource instance_count number value", count_key, "3"
    Let mon_value be proc block_attr_value with resource_block, "monitoring"
    Let mon_key be proc value_key with mon_value
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "resource monitoring bool value", mon_key, "true"
    Let tags_value be proc block_attr_value with resource_block, "tags"
    Let tags_key be proc value_key with tags_value
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "resource tags list has 2 elements", tags_key, "list:2"
    Let res_region_value be proc block_attr_value with resource_block, "region"
    Let res_region_key be proc value_key with res_region_value
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "resource region references var.region", res_region_key, "var.region"
    Let resource_nested be proc block_nested_count with resource_block
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "resource has 1 nested block", resource_nested, 1

    Note: --- output block referencing the resource ---
    Let output_block be proc find_block with hir1, "output", "web_id"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "output \"web_id\" present", output_block
    Let output_value be proc block_attr_value with output_block, "value"
    Let output_value_key be proc value_key with output_value
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "output value references aws_instance.web.id", output_value_key, "aws_instance.web.id"

    Note: --- data source block ---
    Let data_block be proc find_block with hir1, "data", "aws_ami"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "data \"aws_ami\" present", data_block
    Let data_name be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with data_block, "hcl_data_name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "data source name is 'ubuntu'", data_name, "ubuntu"

    Note: --- Stage 2: HIR1 -> HCL text ---
    Let emitted be proc generate_hcl_from_hir from HCLBackend with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "backend produced HCL text", emitted
    Let emitted_len be proc string_length from StringCore with emitted
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "emitted HCL is non-empty", emitted_len, 0

    Note: --- Stage 3: re-parse emitted text -> HIR2, assert SECOND-emission survival ---
    Let hir2 be proc hcl_source_to_hir with emitted
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parse of emitted HCL produced HIR", hir2

    Let decl_count2 be proc module_decl_count with hir2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "second emission preserves declaration count", decl_count2, 7

    Note: Re-locate every block in HIR2 and assert kinds/labels/values survived.
    Let provider2 be proc find_block with hir2, "provider", "aws"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "2nd: provider \"aws\" survived", provider2
    Let provider2_region_value be proc block_attr_value with provider2, "region"
    Let provider2_region be proc value_key with provider2_region_value
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "2nd: provider region still var.region", provider2_region, "var.region"

    Let variable2 be proc find_block with hir2, "variable", "region"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "2nd: variable \"region\" survived", variable2
    Let var2_default_value be proc block_attr_value with variable2, "default"
    Let var2_default be proc value_key with var2_default_value
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "2nd: variable default still 'us-east-1'", var2_default, "us-east-1"

    Let resource2 be proc find_block with hir2, "resource", "aws_instance"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "2nd: resource aws_instance survived", resource2
    Let res2_name be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with resource2, "hcl_resource_name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "2nd: resource name still 'web'", res2_name, "web"
    Let ami2_value be proc block_attr_value with resource2, "ami"
    Let ami2_key be proc value_key with ami2_value
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "2nd: resource ami value survived", ami2_key, "ami-12345"
    Let count2_value be proc block_attr_value with resource2, "instance_count"
    Let count2_key be proc value_key with count2_value
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "2nd: resource instance_count value survived", count2_key, "3"
    Let mon2_value be proc block_attr_value with resource2, "monitoring"
    Let mon2_key be proc value_key with mon2_value
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "2nd: resource monitoring value survived", mon2_key, "true"
    Let tags2_value be proc block_attr_value with resource2, "tags"
    Let tags2_key be proc value_key with tags2_value
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "2nd: resource tags list survived (2 elements)", tags2_key, "list:2"
    Let res2_region_value be proc block_attr_value with resource2, "region"
    Let res2_region be proc value_key with res2_region_value
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "2nd: resource region reference survived", res2_region, "var.region"
    Let resource2_nested be proc block_nested_count with resource2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "2nd: resource nested block survived", resource2_nested, 1

    Let output2 be proc find_block with hir2, "output", "web_id"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "2nd: output \"web_id\" survived", output2
    Let output2_value_node be proc block_attr_value with output2, "value"
    Let output2_value be proc value_key with output2_value_node
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "2nd: output value reference survived", output2_value, "aws_instance.web.id"

    Let data2 be proc find_block with hir2, "data", "aws_ami"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "2nd: data \"aws_ami\" survived", data2
    Let data2_name be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with data2, "hcl_data_name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "2nd: data source name still 'ubuntu'", data2_name, "ubuntu"

    Note: --- Full recursive structural equality between the two HIR modules ---
    Let structurally_equal be proc modules_structurally_equal with hir1, hir2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip HIR is structurally equal", structurally_equal, 1

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process
